metadata.name: TRASH Erector V 1.0  #90
metadata.description:
TRASH Erector V 1.0  is a generative #trashart project by video artist INA VARE.
Elements are created from analog glitched photos and hand-drawn graffiti. Each piece is generated within a wide range of predefined rarity features so you can have a lot of fun by minting these unique artworks. Creative coding animations included. 

-> Click on the image to hide and erect the trash.

Any similarities to known crypto space personas and/or cameo appearances is not a coincidence.

Project by INA VARE, 2022.
Coding: Metimus

metadata.name: el inefable momento #55
metadata.description:
"el inefable momento del colorido descubrimiento" ("the ineffable moment of the colorful discovery")  is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

It is a tribute to playful discovery. This work was commissioned for the Art Basel Hong Kong / Tezos / fxhash collaboration, as part of an activity to introduce visitors into generative art. As I was pondering what could I do in the short time available, I saw my youngest daughter drawing: the ineffable moment of colorful discovery. Child play is one of the most discovery-filled activities I can think of. And drawing is that joy that I describe: a blank piece of paper with a crayon is pure possibility. Which is what generative art is. I had wanted for quite some time to create a tribute to those drawings my daughters do, and this has been the perfect occasion to start it: it seemed to me that it fit the occasion perfectly: kids discover through painting, maybe adults can discover generative art using the same visual language.

"el inefable momento del colorido descubrimiento" is a work that explores colour and irregular basic shapes, and that leaves the viewer in front of a new space with each execution. Does it trigger any excitement to see those imperfect elements? It is dearest to me to see the hearts and rainbows, as two mainstays of the drawings that I keep in folders and count in the hundreds and thousands. Can an algorithm that reproduces those elements trigger the same warm feelings in the viewer? It does with me.

The piece lets the viewer explore certain characteristics. The viewer can pause the iterations: each is just an execution of the same drawing, slightly different. When paused, one can look at each line individually and notice how the drawing is constructed. When running, it gives an idea of how the things we know are just versions of the ideal concept they represent. 

Also, one can have an idea of what would have happened if the child had decided to draw more or less elements. The viewer can press ‚Äúe‚Äù to see different variations of the same piece: random elements are selected and displayed. To restore the original work, press ‚Äúr‚Äù. Which one is the ‚Äúfinished‚Äù artwork? All of them. What is ‚Äúthe‚Äù artwork? 

The work has the following commands:

- Change the work: ‚Äúe‚Äù. To restore: ‚Äúr‚Äù
- The painting can be paused/unpaused pressing ‚Äúp‚Äù
- The viewer can save an artwork pressing ‚Äús‚Äù (it will pause the piece, press "p" to unpause)
- The resolution can be arbitrarily changed pressing ‚Äúd‚Äù followed by a number from 1 to 9. If the image goes dark and nothing paints, press ‚Äúd 0‚Äù (d zero) and try again with a lower number. Resolution can be increased iteratively: press d 2, then d 2, etc. It will always add the amount to the current pixel density, thus increasing resolution.
- The viewer can see how many decisions are made per iteration. This might be interesting to those who don‚Äôt know how generative art works. Each iteration is composed of thousands of decisions that inform colour, positions, shapes, etc. To toggle the decision count view, press ‚Äúq‚Äù
- It has also colour controls: press z for brightness, x for contrast, g for gamma, b for blur, n for noise followed by + or - to alter their values. You might get some simple variations that you might enjoy. Press a to enable/disable all colour controls (except the noise).
- There are some pre-recorded colour variations: press ‚Äúv‚Äù followed by 1, 2 or 3. Press ‚Äúv‚Äù followed by 0 (zero) to reset the variations.

In every process of discovery, one comes to an "aha" moment ;) If you find your aha moment, then you can do one more thing: you can play with the size of certain elements pressing ‚Äúo‚Äù. To restore, reload the piece. Once you find your aha moment, you can go back the same way you got there. All the controls work the same when one has reached their aha moment.

I hope you enjoy the piece as much as I have enjoyed drawing it, directly or indirectly, with my daughters. Thanks.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro.
Made with p5js and glsl.

metadata.name: Storm Chamber | Collab with Somfay #2
metadata.description:
Generative art piece created with code in Hydra and in collaboration with artist @s0mfay

This piece arises from the absolute need to combine our styles. On the one hand, the evocative intensity of Somfay's color and that storm of shapes and movement that characterizes my work. The result is this explosive and dramatic piece that feels like a storm in a room full of liquid and high energy.

Hydra is a toolkit for live coding of network visuals created by Olivia Jack (ojack.xyz)

Collab by Somfay & Daniel Oropeza
Panama City, Panama
18/05/2022

metadata.name: Mirage 001 #24
metadata.description:
Mirage 001-The first in a series of three works that explore 3D space, light, and composition. The animation takes 2.30min to complete the draw so sit back and enjoy. The first 30 collectors of the generative token will gain access-list to the next two Mirage releases. Please contact Zero Alpha if you wish to obtain a custom high-resolution file of your minted token. Thank you for collecting this work.

-3 Background environments
-9 Colour palettes each with 5 colours to the set
-2 Rare colour pallets

*This generator is optimized to be viewed on a desktop computer with decent GPU at
resolutions over 1000x1000px
*Reload the browser to start the animation from the beginning.
*2.30min to complete draw please be patient

metadata.name: Lines and Planes #32
metadata.description:
A series of lines and planes intersect at random angles in varying densities and color schemes to create an ever changing composition. Each iteration is unique. Rarity features work as follows :
1. Black backgrounds are common, white - less common and red - very rare.
2. Density of lines and planes are less common with increase in density.
3. Angle distribution are almost uniformly distributed.

metadata.name: Averno #25
metadata.description:
The work sits at the intersection of atmospheric abstraction and symbolic representation,
where generative aesthetics become a vehicle for an exploration of the perceptual threshold between form and dissolution.
Vertical structures, resembling slender shrubs or nervous filaments, construct a visual lattice that oscillates between transparency and density, suggesting a synthetic vegetation suspended between nature and algorithm.

The composition stands out for its use of digital color, with gradients that simulate traditional techniques such as pastel or watercolor, while maintaining a coherence typical of code. The generative intervention is not merely ornamental: it is a formal strategy that translates the indeterminacy of the landscape into an autonomous aesthetic language.

The sinuous shapes that emerge from below and rise upwards are not mere presences: they suggest a humanity in the making‚Äîor rather, an anthropomorphic echo generated by the system, a tension between organic mark-making and computational logic.

metadata.name: Hegemony Of Screensavers (Toubab) #45
metadata.description: Suspended in a deep ambivalence. Thulien Pink and Rose Gold. The Earth is red in Senegal. The rocks along the coast are volcanic. I scanned one on the beach, clambering about in non-deterministic orbits. A local man arrived and earnestly explained how the rock had a face and it held the spirits of their ancestors. His pained expression made it clear ‚Äì I was violating the ancestral stone with my camera. I was that plundering colonialist. My first mobile phone was expensive for 1999, around $350. I didn‚Äôt need it, I just wanted it. I still have it. Carmine Red, Grey and Platinum.
